<DOC><DOCNO> AP891109-0006 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0029EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-Secord-Chronology     11-09 0306</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Secord-Chronology,0315</SECOND><HEAD>With PM-Secord Plea</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here is a chronology of retired Air Force Maj.Gen. Richard Secord's involvement in the Iran-Contra affair:   1983: Secord leaves the government under a cloud concerning histies to Edwin P. Wilson, a former CIA agent convicted in 1983 ofillegally shipping munitions to Libya and plotting to kill anopponent of Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi.   1984: Secord, an expert in handling covert operations, beginsselling arms to the Contras at the request of White House aideOliver North. North says he got Secord's name from CIA DirectorWilliam Casey about the time U.S. aid to the Contras was runningout and Congress was barring the intelligence agency from supplyingthe rebels with military aid.   Late 1985: North brings Secord into the Reagan administration'ssecret arms initiative with Iran.   October-November 1986: One of the North network's planes is shotdown over Nicaragua and the administration's arms sales to Iran areexposed. Also uncovered is the diversion of Iran arms sale money tothe Contras through the complex of secret accounts operated bySecord and his business partner Albert Hakim.   May 1987: Secord is the first witness in the congressionalIran-Contra hearings. In four days of testimony, he says that:   _He assumed President Reagan knew of his activities.   _He forswore profits in the Iran-Contra operation, never gettingany money besides his $6,000-a-month salary.   March 16, 1988: Secord, North, Hakim and former NationalSecurity Adviser John Poindexter are indicted following a criminalinvestigation by independent counsel Lawrence Walsh. A federaljudge ultimately decides the defendants must be tried separately,and North later is convicted on three counts.   Nov. 8, 1989: Secord pleads guilty to a single felony,concerning lying to Congress about financial help he gave North,five days before his trial is to begin on 12 criminal charges.</TEXT></DOC>